00:00:23.170 --> 00:00:28.900
PROFESSOR: Today we're going to
continue our discussion of

00:00:28.900 --> 00:00:33.040
methods of integration.

00:00:33.040 --> 00:00:36.550
The method that I'm going to
describe today handles a whole

00:00:36.550 --> 00:00:40.510
class of functions of
the following form.

00:00:40.510 --> 00:00:45.870
You take P (x) / Q (x)
and this is known

00:00:45.870 --> 00:00:53.460
as a rational function.

00:00:53.460 --> 00:01:01.090
And all that means is that
it's a ratio off two

00:01:01.090 --> 00:01:13.300
polynomials, which are these
functions P ( x) and Q ( x).

00:01:13.300 --> 00:01:17.560
We'll handle all such functions
by a method which is

00:01:17.560 --> 00:01:26.250
known as partial fractions.

00:01:26.250 --> 00:01:36.300
And what this does is, it splits
P / Q into what you

00:01:36.300 --> 00:01:45.260
could call easier pieces.

00:01:45.260 --> 00:01:48.030
So that's going to be some
kind of algebra.

00:01:48.030 --> 00:01:49.380
And that's what we're going
to spend most of

00:01:49.380 --> 00:01:52.640
our time doing today.

00:01:52.640 --> 00:01:55.090
I'll start with an example.

00:01:55.090 --> 00:01:58.950
And all of my examples
will be illustrating

00:01:58.950 --> 00:02:01.830
more general methods.

00:02:01.830 --> 00:02:08.200
The example is to integrate the
function 1 / x - 1 +, say,

00:02:08.200 --> 00:02:15.240
3 / x + 2 dx.

00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:17.400
That's easy to do.

00:02:17.400 --> 00:02:19.410
It's just, we already
know the answer.

00:02:19.410 --> 00:02:26.780
It's ln x - 1 + 3 ln x + 3.

00:02:26.780 --> 00:02:28.340
Plus a constant.

00:02:28.340 --> 00:02:37.050
So that's done.

00:02:37.050 --> 00:02:41.330
So now, here's the difficulty
that is going to arise.

00:02:41.330 --> 00:02:45.070
The difficulty is that I can
start with this function,

00:02:45.070 --> 00:02:49.210
which is perfectly manageable.

00:02:49.210 --> 00:02:52.830
And than I can add these
two functions together.

00:02:52.830 --> 00:02:55.380
The way I add fractions.

00:02:55.380 --> 00:03:00.750
So that's getting a common
denominator.

00:03:00.750 --> 00:03:06.645
And so that gives me x +
2 here + 3 ( x - 1).

00:03:06.645 --> 00:03:11.550
And now if I combine together
all of these terms, then

00:03:11.550 --> 00:03:16.960
altogether I have 4x +
2 - 3, that's - 1.

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:23.690
And if I multiply out the
denominator that's x ^2 + that

00:03:23.690 --> 00:03:28.060
2 turned into a 3, that's
interesting.

00:03:28.060 --> 00:03:31.240
Hope there aren't too many more
of those transformations.

00:03:31.240 --> 00:03:32.570
Is there another one here?

00:03:32.570 --> 00:03:36.830
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:03:36.830 --> 00:03:39.150
PROFESSOR: Oh, it happened
earlier on.

00:03:39.150 --> 00:03:42.620
Wow that's an interesting
vibration there.

00:03:42.620 --> 00:03:45.510
OK.

00:03:45.510 --> 00:03:50.500
Thank you.

00:03:50.500 --> 00:03:56.770
So, I guess my 3's were
speaking to my 2's.

00:03:56.770 --> 00:04:00.610
Somewhere in my past.
OK, anyway, I

00:04:00.610 --> 00:04:07.200
think this is now correct.

00:04:07.200 --> 00:04:10.020
So the problem is
the following.

00:04:10.020 --> 00:04:11.450
This is the problem with this.

00:04:11.450 --> 00:04:14.830
This integral was easy.

00:04:14.830 --> 00:04:18.500
I'm calling it easy, we already
know how to do it.

00:04:18.500 --> 00:04:19.450
Over here.

00:04:19.450 --> 00:04:28.040
But now over here,
it's disguised.

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:32.270
It's the same function, but it's
no longer clear how to

00:04:32.270 --> 00:04:32.780
integrate it.

00:04:32.780 --> 00:04:34.990
If you're faced with this
one, you say what am

00:04:34.990 --> 00:04:38.480
I supposed to do.

00:04:38.480 --> 00:04:41.790
And we have to get around
that difficulty.

00:04:41.790 --> 00:04:44.205
And so what we're going
to do is we're going

00:04:44.205 --> 00:04:46.660
to unwind this disguise.

00:04:46.660 --> 00:04:57.950
So we have the algebra problem
that we have. Oh, wow.

00:04:57.950 --> 00:04:59.510
There must be something
in the water.

00:04:59.510 --> 00:05:06.280
Impressive.

00:05:06.280 --> 00:05:06.920
Wow.

00:05:06.920 --> 00:05:08.350
OK, let's see.

00:05:08.350 --> 00:05:14.660
Is 2/3 = 3/2?

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:17.960
Holy cow.

00:05:17.960 --> 00:05:18.760
Well that's good.

00:05:18.760 --> 00:05:21.340
Well, I'll keep you awake
today with several other

00:05:21.340 --> 00:05:23.940
transpositions here.

00:05:23.940 --> 00:05:30.760
So our algebra problem is to
detect the easy pieces which

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:36.290
are inside.

00:05:36.290 --> 00:05:38.850
And the method that we're going
to use, the one that

00:05:38.850 --> 00:05:43.880
we'll emphasize anyway, is one
algebraic trick which is a

00:05:43.880 --> 00:05:49.320
shortcut, which is called
the cover-up method.

00:05:49.320 --> 00:05:51.170
But we're going to talk
about even more

00:05:51.170 --> 00:05:52.510
general things than that.

00:05:52.510 --> 00:05:54.300
But anyway, this is where
we're headed.

00:05:54.300 --> 00:05:57.910
Is something called the
cover-up method.

00:05:57.910 --> 00:05:59.490
Alright.

00:05:59.490 --> 00:06:02.640
So that's our intro.

00:06:02.640 --> 00:06:05.765
And I'll just have to remember
that 2 is not 3.

00:06:05.765 --> 00:06:08.130
I'll keep on repeating that.

00:06:08.130 --> 00:06:12.240
So now here I'm going to
describe to you how we unwind

00:06:12.240 --> 00:06:13.880
this disguise.

00:06:13.880 --> 00:06:16.990
The first step is,
we write down the

00:06:16.990 --> 00:06:18.690
function we want to integrate.

00:06:18.690 --> 00:06:21.890
Which was this.

00:06:21.890 --> 00:06:26.310
And now we have to undo the
first damage that we did.

00:06:26.310 --> 00:06:31.930
So the first step is to factor
the denominator.

00:06:31.930 --> 00:06:34.580
And that factors, we happen to
know the factors, so I'm not

00:06:34.580 --> 00:06:36.150
going to carry this out.

00:06:36.150 --> 00:06:38.510
But this can be a rather
difficult step.

00:06:38.510 --> 00:06:41.110
But we're going to assume
that it's done.

00:06:41.110 --> 00:06:44.030
For the purposes of
illustration here.

00:06:44.030 --> 00:06:46.780
So I factor the denominator.

00:06:46.780 --> 00:06:51.730
And now, the second thing that
I'm going to do is what I'm

00:06:51.730 --> 00:06:54.770
going to call the setup here.

00:06:54.770 --> 00:06:56.520
How I'm going to
set things up.

00:06:56.520 --> 00:07:00.100
And I'll tell you what these
things are more systematically

00:07:00.100 --> 00:07:01.010
in a second.

00:07:01.010 --> 00:07:03.210
And the setup is that
I want to somehow

00:07:03.210 --> 00:07:05.240
detect what I did before.

00:07:05.240 --> 00:07:11.880
And I'm going to write
some unknowns here.

00:07:11.880 --> 00:07:15.650
What I expect is that this will
break up into two pieces.

00:07:15.650 --> 00:07:18.060
One with the denominator x -
1, and the other with the

00:07:18.060 --> 00:07:23.470
denominator x + 2.

00:07:23.470 --> 00:07:32.860
So now, my third step is going
to be to solve for A and B.

00:07:32.860 --> 00:07:34.500
And then I'm done,
if I do that.

00:07:34.500 --> 00:07:41.370
That's the complete unwinding
of this disguise.

00:07:41.370 --> 00:07:43.940
And this is where the cover-up
method comes in handy.

00:07:43.940 --> 00:07:46.800
This is this method that
I'm about to describe.

00:07:46.800 --> 00:07:49.920
Now, you can do the algebra in a
clumsy way, or you can do it

00:07:49.920 --> 00:07:50.970
in a quick way.

00:07:50.970 --> 00:07:54.240
And we'd like to get efficient
about the algebra involved.

00:07:54.240 --> 00:07:57.450
And so let me show you
what the first step

00:07:57.450 --> 00:07:58.590
in the trick is.

00:07:58.590 --> 00:08:12.470
We're going to solve for A by
multiplying by (x - 1).

00:08:12.470 --> 00:08:16.080
Now, notice if you multiply by
(x - 1) in that equation 2,

00:08:16.080 --> 00:08:16.920
what you get is this.

00:08:16.920 --> 00:08:21.840
You got 4x - 2 / the
x - 1's cancel.

00:08:21.840 --> 00:08:23.920
You get this on the
left-hand side.

00:08:23.920 --> 00:08:27.870
And on the right-hand side
you get A. The x

00:08:27.870 --> 00:08:29.620
- 1's cancel again.

00:08:29.620 --> 00:08:31.420
And then we get this
extra term.

00:08:31.420 --> 00:08:35.200
Which is B/ ( x + 2)( x - 1).

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:39.200
Now, the trick here, and we're
going to get even better trick

00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:40.370
in just a second.

00:08:40.370 --> 00:08:42.970
The trick here is that I
didn't try to clear the

00:08:42.970 --> 00:08:44.560
denominators completely.

00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:46.820
I was very efficient about
the way I did it.

00:08:46.820 --> 00:08:51.390
It just cleared one factor.

00:08:51.390 --> 00:08:54.780
And the result here
is very useful.

00:08:54.780 --> 00:09:03.480
Namely, if I plug in now x =
1, this term drops out too.

00:09:03.480 --> 00:09:10.560
So what I'm going to do now is
I'm going to plug in x = 1.

00:09:10.560 --> 00:09:13.970
And what I get on the left-hand
side here is 4 - 1

00:09:13.970 --> 00:09:16.550
and 1 + 2, and on the
left-hand side I get

00:09:16.550 --> 00:09:19.740
A. That's the end.

00:09:19.740 --> 00:09:27.150
This is my formula for A. A
happens to be equal to 1.

00:09:27.150 --> 00:09:29.100
And that's, of course,
what I expect.

00:09:29.100 --> 00:09:33.340
A had better be 1, because the
thing broke up into 1 / x - 1

00:09:33.340 --> 00:09:37.100
+ 3 / x + 2.

00:09:37.100 --> 00:09:39.900
So this is the correct answer.

00:09:39.900 --> 00:09:41.610
There was a question out
here, which I missed.

00:09:41.610 --> 00:09:48.560
STUDENT: Aren't polynomials
defined as functions with

00:09:48.560 --> 00:09:56.210
whole powers, or could
they be square roots?

00:09:56.210 --> 00:09:58.300
PROFESSOR: Are polynomials
defined as functions with

00:09:58.300 --> 00:10:00.330
whole powers, or can they
be square roots?

00:10:00.330 --> 00:10:01.350
That's the question.

00:10:01.350 --> 00:10:04.140
The answer is, they only
have whole powers.

00:10:04.140 --> 00:10:06.950
So for instance here I only
have the power 1 and 0.

00:10:06.950 --> 00:10:10.410
Here I have the powers 2, 1
and 0 in the denominator.

00:10:10.410 --> 00:10:16.890
Square roots are no good
for this method.

00:10:16.890 --> 00:10:17.670
Another question.

00:10:17.670 --> 00:10:18.620
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:10:18.620 --> 00:10:22.260
PROFESSOR: Why did
I say x = 1?

00:10:22.260 --> 00:10:26.650
The reason why I said x = 1 was
that it works really fast.

00:10:26.650 --> 00:10:27.910
You can't know this in advance,

00:10:27.910 --> 00:10:30.400
that's part of the method.

00:10:30.400 --> 00:10:32.810
It just turns out to be
the best thing to do.

00:10:32.810 --> 00:10:36.360
The fastest way of getting at
the coefficient A. Now the

00:10:36.360 --> 00:10:38.210
curious thing, let me
just pause for a

00:10:38.210 --> 00:10:39.320
second before I do it.

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:44.010
If I had plugged x = 1 into the
original equation, I would

00:10:44.010 --> 00:10:45.070
have gotten nonsense.

00:10:45.070 --> 00:10:48.210
Because I would've gotten
0 in the denominator.

00:10:48.210 --> 00:10:50.940
And that seems like the most
horrible thing to do.

00:10:50.940 --> 00:10:54.280
The worst possible thing
to do, is to set x = 1.

00:10:54.280 --> 00:10:56.490
On the other hand, what
we did is a trick.

00:10:56.490 --> 00:10:58.870
We multiplied by x - 1.

00:10:58.870 --> 00:11:01.100
And that turned the equation
into this.

00:11:01.100 --> 00:11:05.810
So now, in disguise,
I multiplied by 0.

00:11:05.810 --> 00:11:07.890
But that turns out
to be legitimate.

00:11:07.890 --> 00:11:11.770
Because really this equation
is true for all x except 1.

00:11:11.770 --> 00:11:13.880
And then instead of taking
x = 1, I can really

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:15.580
take x tends to 1.

00:11:15.580 --> 00:11:17.200
That's really what I need.

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:18.530
The limit is x goes to one.

00:11:18.530 --> 00:11:20.610
The equation is still
valid then.

00:11:20.610 --> 00:11:23.220
So I'm using the worst case, the
case that looks like it's

00:11:23.220 --> 00:11:24.360
dividing by 0.

00:11:24.360 --> 00:11:26.870
And it's helping me because it's
cancelling out all the

00:11:26.870 --> 00:11:31.730
information in terms of B. So
the advantage here is this

00:11:31.730 --> 00:11:36.090
cancellation that occurs
in this part.

00:11:36.090 --> 00:11:37.440
So that's the method.

00:11:37.440 --> 00:11:39.930
We're going to shorten it much,
much more in a second.

00:11:39.930 --> 00:11:44.640
But let me carry it out for the
other coefficient as well.

00:11:44.640 --> 00:11:51.700
So the other coefficient I'm
going to solve for B, I'm

00:11:51.700 --> 00:11:57.490
going to multiply by x + 2.

00:11:57.490 --> 00:12:01.620
And when I do that, I get 4x
- 1 / x - 1, that's the

00:12:01.620 --> 00:12:05.020
left-hand side, the very
top expression there.

00:12:05.020 --> 00:12:10.700
And then down below I get
A/ ( x - 1)( x + 2).

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:14.380
And then again the
x + 2's cancel.

00:12:14.380 --> 00:12:15.960
So I get B sitting alone.

00:12:15.960 --> 00:12:18.150
And now I'm going to
do the same trick.

00:12:18.150 --> 00:12:21.540
I'm going to set x = - 2.

00:12:21.540 --> 00:12:27.270
That's the value which
is going to knock

00:12:27.270 --> 00:12:28.530
out this A term here.

00:12:28.530 --> 00:12:30.770
So that cancels this
term completely.

00:12:30.770 --> 00:12:37.950
And what we get here all told
is - 8 - 1 / - 2 - 1 = B. In

00:12:37.950 --> 00:12:43.090
other words, B = 3, which
was also what it

00:12:43.090 --> 00:12:44.100
was supposed to be.

00:12:44.100 --> 00:12:48.460
B was this number
3, right here.

00:12:48.460 --> 00:12:50.820
Which I'm now not going
to change to 2.

00:12:50.820 --> 00:12:52.600
Because I know that
it's not 2.

00:12:52.600 --> 00:12:53.370
There was a question.

00:12:53.370 --> 00:12:59.540
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:12:59.540 --> 00:13:01.420
PROFESSOR: All right.

00:13:01.420 --> 00:13:05.770
Now, this is the method which
is called cover-up.

00:13:05.770 --> 00:13:09.490
But it's really carried out
much, much faster than this.

00:13:09.490 --> 00:13:11.880
So I'm going to review the
method and I'm going to show

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:14.300
you what it is in general.

00:13:14.300 --> 00:13:23.030
So the first step is to factor
the denominator, Q. That's

00:13:23.030 --> 00:13:24.590
what I labeled 1 over there.

00:13:24.590 --> 00:13:29.350
That was the factorization of
the denominator up top.

00:13:29.350 --> 00:13:36.260
The second step is what I'm
going to call the setup.

00:13:36.260 --> 00:13:37.250
That's step 2.

00:13:37.250 --> 00:13:41.060
And that's where I knew what I
was aiming for in advance.

00:13:41.060 --> 00:13:42.990
And I'm going to have to
explain to you in every

00:13:42.990 --> 00:13:45.780
instance exactly what this
setup should be.

00:13:45.780 --> 00:13:49.070
That is, what the unknowns
should be and what target,

00:13:49.070 --> 00:13:53.080
simplified expression,
we're aiming for.

00:13:53.080 --> 00:13:54.950
So that's the setup.

00:13:54.950 --> 00:14:01.010
And then the third step is what
I'll now call cover-up.

00:14:01.010 --> 00:14:04.300
Which is just a very fast way
of doing what I did on this

00:14:04.300 --> 00:14:09.470
last board, which is solving for
the unknown coefficients.

00:14:09.470 --> 00:14:12.890
So now, let me perform
it for you again.

00:14:12.890 --> 00:14:14.170
Over here.

00:14:14.170 --> 00:14:17.750
So it's 4x - 1 divided
by, so this is to

00:14:17.750 --> 00:14:19.650
eliminate writing here.

00:14:19.650 --> 00:14:24.130
Handwriting it makes
it much faster.

00:14:24.130 --> 00:14:29.920
So this part just factoring the
denominator, that was 1,

00:14:29.920 --> 00:14:31.290
that was step 1.

00:14:31.290 --> 00:14:34.320
And then step 2, again,
is the setup, which is

00:14:34.320 --> 00:14:39.700
setting it up like this.

00:14:39.700 --> 00:14:42.580
Alright, that's the setup.

00:14:42.580 --> 00:14:46.540
And now I claim that without
writing very much, I can

00:14:46.540 --> 00:14:49.350
figure out what A and B are.

00:14:49.350 --> 00:14:51.350
Just by staring at this.

00:14:51.350 --> 00:14:54.470
So now what I'm going to do is
I'm just going to think what I

00:14:54.470 --> 00:14:55.720
did over there.

00:14:55.720 --> 00:14:57.570
And I'm just going to
do it directly.

00:14:57.570 --> 00:15:02.680
So let me show you what the
method consists of visually.

00:15:02.680 --> 00:15:09.200
I'm going to cover up, that is,
knock out this factor, and

00:15:09.200 --> 00:15:13.560
focus on this number here.

00:15:13.560 --> 00:15:16.240
And I'm going to plug in the
thing that makes the 0,

00:15:16.240 --> 00:15:17.580
which is x = 1.

00:15:17.580 --> 00:15:20.180
So I'm plugging in x = 1.

00:15:20.180 --> 00:15:21.670
To this left-hand side.

00:15:21.670 --> 00:15:29.040
And what I get is 4 - 1 / 1 +
2 = A. Now, that's the same

00:15:29.040 --> 00:15:29.820
thing I did over there.

00:15:29.820 --> 00:15:33.610
I just did it by skipping the
intermediate algebra step,

00:15:33.610 --> 00:15:35.860
which is a lot of writing.

00:15:35.860 --> 00:15:37.940
So the cover-up method
really amounts to

00:15:37.940 --> 00:15:38.580
the following thing.

00:15:38.580 --> 00:15:40.385
I'm thinking of multiplying
this over here.

00:15:40.385 --> 00:15:43.240
It cancels this and it gets
rid of everything else.

00:15:43.240 --> 00:15:45.960
And it just leaves me with
A on the right-hand side.

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:47.680
And I have to get rid
of it on this side.

00:15:47.680 --> 00:15:50.360
So in other words, by
eliminating this, I'm

00:15:50.360 --> 00:15:53.090
isolating a on the
right-hand side.

00:15:53.090 --> 00:15:55.860
So the cover-up is that
I'm covering this and

00:15:55.860 --> 00:15:57.670
getting A out of it.

00:15:57.670 --> 00:16:02.330
Similarly, I can do the same
thing with B. It's focused on

00:16:02.330 --> 00:16:04.720
the value x = - 2.

00:16:04.720 --> 00:16:07.010
And b is what I'm getting
on the right-hand side.

00:16:07.010 --> 00:16:10.400
And then I have to
cover up this.

00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:14.530
So if I cover up that, then
what's left over with x = - 2

00:16:14.530 --> 00:16:22.580
is again, - 8 - 1 / - 2 - 1.

00:16:22.580 --> 00:16:26.970
So this is the way the method
gets carried out in practice.

00:16:26.970 --> 00:16:32.070
Writing, essentially,
the least you can.

00:16:32.070 --> 00:16:40.140
Now, when you get to several
variables, it becomes just way

00:16:40.140 --> 00:16:42.170
more convenient to do this.

00:16:42.170 --> 00:16:45.660
So now, let me just review
when cover-up works.

00:16:45.660 --> 00:16:57.370
So this cover-up method
works if Q ( x) has

00:16:57.370 --> 00:17:06.060
distinct linear factors.

00:17:06.060 --> 00:17:11.780
And, so you need two
things here.

00:17:11.780 --> 00:17:14.570
It has to factor completely, the
denominator has to factor

00:17:14.570 --> 00:17:15.180
completely.

00:17:15.180 --> 00:17:20.920
And the degree of the numerator
has to be strictly

00:17:20.920 --> 00:17:27.750
less than the degree
of the denominator.

00:17:27.750 --> 00:17:30.080
I'm going to give you
an example here.

00:17:30.080 --> 00:17:36.010
So, for instance, and this tells
you the general pattern

00:17:36.010 --> 00:17:38.070
of the setup also.

00:17:38.070 --> 00:17:44.090
Say you had x ^2 + 3x
+ 8, let's say.

00:17:44.090 --> 00:17:50.380
Over (x - 1) ( x - 2)( x + 5).

00:17:50.380 --> 00:17:52.920
So here I'm going to
tell you the setup.

00:17:52.920 --> 00:17:58.710
The setup is going to be
A / (x - 1) + B / (x -

00:17:58.710 --> 00:18:02.820
2) + c / x + 5.

00:18:02.820 --> 00:18:04.620
And it will always break
up into something.

00:18:04.620 --> 00:18:07.570
So however many factors you
have, you'll have to put in a

00:18:07.570 --> 00:18:09.770
term for each of those.

00:18:09.770 --> 00:18:13.300
And then you can find
each number here by

00:18:13.300 --> 00:18:26.060
this cover-up method.

00:18:26.060 --> 00:18:29.450
Now we're done with that.

00:18:29.450 --> 00:18:33.280
And now we have to go on to the
algebraic complications.

00:18:33.280 --> 00:18:38.420
So would the first typical
algebraic complication be.

00:18:38.420 --> 00:18:50.760
It would be repeated roots
or repeated factors.

00:18:50.760 --> 00:18:54.190
Let me get one that doesn't
come out to be

00:18:54.190 --> 00:18:56.850
extremely ugly here.

00:18:56.850 --> 00:19:02.930
So this is what we'll
call Example 2.

00:19:02.930 --> 00:19:06.510
And this is going to work when
the degree, you always need

00:19:06.510 --> 00:19:08.650
that the degree of the numerator
is less than the

00:19:08.650 --> 00:19:12.060
degree of the denominator.

00:19:12.060 --> 00:19:22.980
And Q has now repeated
linear factors.

00:19:22.980 --> 00:19:26.030
So let's see which example
I wanted to show you.

00:19:26.030 --> 00:19:28.830
So let's just give this here.

00:19:28.830 --> 00:19:34.080
I'll just repeat the
denominator.

00:19:34.080 --> 00:19:39.580
With an extra factor
like this.

00:19:39.580 --> 00:19:42.110
Now, the main thing you need
to know, since I've already

00:19:42.110 --> 00:19:44.370
performed the factorization
for you.

00:19:44.370 --> 00:19:46.140
Already performed Step 1.

00:19:46.140 --> 00:19:49.350
This is Step 1 here.

00:19:49.350 --> 00:19:51.540
You have to factor things all
the way, and that's already

00:19:51.540 --> 00:19:53.910
been done for you.

00:19:53.910 --> 00:19:56.840
And here's what this setup is.

00:19:56.840 --> 00:20:01.820
The setup is that it's of
the form A / (x - 1)

00:20:01.820 --> 00:20:05.540
+ B / (x - 1) ^2.

00:20:05.540 --> 00:20:15.590
We need another term for the
square here. + C / (x + 2).

00:20:15.590 --> 00:20:17.950
In general, if you have more
powers you just need to keep

00:20:17.950 --> 00:20:19.310
on putting in those powers.

00:20:19.310 --> 00:20:24.140
You need one for each
of the powers.

00:20:24.140 --> 00:20:26.340
Why does it have to be squared?

00:20:26.340 --> 00:20:27.570
OK.

00:20:27.570 --> 00:20:28.680
Good question.

00:20:28.680 --> 00:20:31.660
So why in the world
am I doing this?

00:20:31.660 --> 00:20:37.070
Let me just give you one hint
as to why I'm doing this.

00:20:37.070 --> 00:20:41.600
It's very, very much like the
decimal expansion of a number

00:20:41.600 --> 00:20:44.820
or, say, the base 2 expansion
of a number.

00:20:44.820 --> 00:20:57.750
So, for, example the number 7/16
is 0 / 2 + 1 / 2 ^2 + 1/2

00:20:57.750 --> 00:21:02.120
^3 +, is that right?

00:21:02.120 --> 00:21:07.300
So it's 4/16 + 1/2 ^4.

00:21:07.300 --> 00:21:09.090
It's this sort of thing.

00:21:09.090 --> 00:21:11.880
And I'm getting this power
and this power.

00:21:11.880 --> 00:21:13.760
If I have higher powers,
I'm going to have to

00:21:13.760 --> 00:21:14.500
have more and more.

00:21:14.500 --> 00:21:17.310
So this is what happens
when I have a 2 ^ 4.

00:21:17.310 --> 00:21:20.550
I have to represent
things like this.

00:21:20.550 --> 00:21:23.840
That's what's coming out
of this piece with the

00:21:23.840 --> 00:21:24.930
repetitious here.

00:21:24.930 --> 00:21:26.390
Of the powers.

00:21:26.390 --> 00:21:31.070
This is just an analogy.

00:21:31.070 --> 00:21:31.930
Of what we're doing.

00:21:31.930 --> 00:21:33.280
Yeah, another question
over here.

00:21:33.280 --> 00:21:34.460
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:21:34.460 --> 00:21:35.080
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:21:35.080 --> 00:21:37.350
So this is an example, but it's
meant to represent the

00:21:37.350 --> 00:21:41.210
general case and I will also
give you a general picture.

00:21:41.210 --> 00:21:43.820
For sure, once you have the
second power here, you'll need

00:21:43.820 --> 00:21:46.790
both the first and the second
power mentioned over here.

00:21:46.790 --> 00:21:48.960
And since there's only a first
power over here I only have to

00:21:48.960 --> 00:21:52.060
mention a first power
over there.

00:21:52.060 --> 00:21:55.790
If this were a 3 here, there
would be one more term which

00:21:55.790 --> 00:22:00.630
would be the one for x - 1
^2 in the denominator.

00:22:00.630 --> 00:22:03.940
That's what you just said.

00:22:03.940 --> 00:22:09.400
OK, now, what's different about
this setup is that the

00:22:09.400 --> 00:22:11.810
cover-up method, although
it works, it

00:22:11.810 --> 00:22:13.120
doesn't work so well.

00:22:13.120 --> 00:22:14.660
It doesn't work quite as well.

00:22:14.660 --> 00:22:33.940
The cover-up works for the
coefficients B and C, not A.

00:22:33.940 --> 00:22:38.710
We'll have a quick method for
the numbers B and C. To figure

00:22:38.710 --> 00:22:40.530
out what they are.

00:22:40.530 --> 00:22:43.820
But it will be a little slower
to get to A, which we will do

00:22:43.820 --> 00:22:56.780
last. Let me show you
how it works.

00:22:56.780 --> 00:23:01.610
First of all, I'm going to do
the ordinary cover-up with C.

00:23:01.610 --> 00:23:05.640
So for C, I just want
to do the same old

00:23:05.640 --> 00:23:06.360
thing that I did before.

00:23:06.360 --> 00:23:10.260
I cover up this, and that's
going to get rid of all the

00:23:10.260 --> 00:23:12.300
junk except for the C term.

00:23:12.300 --> 00:23:16.800
So I have to plug x = - 2.

00:23:16.800 --> 00:23:21.810
And I get x -- sorry, I get (-2
) ^2 + 2 in the numerator.

00:23:21.810 --> 00:23:25.660
And I get (- 2 - 1)^2
in the denominator.

00:23:25.660 --> 00:23:28.690
Remember I'm covering this up.

00:23:28.690 --> 00:23:30.790
So that's all there is on
the left-hand side.

00:23:30.790 --> 00:23:38.300
And on the right-hand side all
there is C. Everything else

00:23:38.300 --> 00:23:40.580
got killed off, because it
was x - 2 times that.

00:23:40.580 --> 00:23:42.570
That's 0 times all
that other stuff.

00:23:42.570 --> 00:23:45.240
And the x - 2 over
here canceled.

00:23:45.240 --> 00:23:47.710
This is the shortcut that I just
described, and this is

00:23:47.710 --> 00:23:50.920
much faster than doing
all that arithmetic.

00:23:50.920 --> 00:23:52.620
And algebra.

00:23:52.620 --> 00:23:57.160
So all together this
is a 6/9, right?

00:23:57.160 --> 00:24:09.140
So it's C = 6/9, which is 2/3.

00:24:09.140 --> 00:24:13.500
Now, the other one which is easy
to do, I'm going to do by

00:24:13.500 --> 00:24:17.350
the slow method first.
But you omit a term.

00:24:17.350 --> 00:24:23.380
The idea is to cover up
the other bad factor.

00:24:23.380 --> 00:24:27.480
Cover ups, I'll do it both
the way and the slow way.

00:24:27.480 --> 00:24:29.330
I'll do it the fast way first,
and then I'll show

00:24:29.330 --> 00:24:30.440
you the slow way.

00:24:30.440 --> 00:24:32.470
The fast way is to
cover this up.

00:24:32.470 --> 00:24:34.300
And then I have to cover
up everything else.

00:24:34.300 --> 00:24:35.740
That gets eliminated.

00:24:35.740 --> 00:24:39.150
And that includes everything
but B. So I

00:24:39.150 --> 00:24:40.950
get B on this side.

00:24:40.950 --> 00:24:42.970
And I get 1 on that side.

00:24:42.970 --> 00:24:48.340
So that's 1 ^2 + 2 / 1 + 2.

00:24:48.340 --> 00:24:56.250
So in other words, B = 1.

00:24:56.250 --> 00:24:58.710
That was pretty fast, so let
me show you what arithmetic

00:24:58.710 --> 00:25:00.060
was hiding behind that.

00:25:00.060 --> 00:25:01.690
What algebra was hiding
behind it.

00:25:01.690 --> 00:25:06.900
What I was really
doing is this.

00:25:06.900 --> 00:25:16.390
In multiplying through by
x - 1 ^2, so I got this.

00:25:16.390 --> 00:25:19.910
So this canceled here, so this
C just stands alone.

00:25:19.910 --> 00:25:26.290
And then I have here C
/x + 2 (x - 1) ^2.

00:25:26.290 --> 00:25:30.910
Notice again, I cleared out
that 1, this term from the

00:25:30.910 --> 00:25:33.600
denominator and sent it over
to the other side.

00:25:33.600 --> 00:25:41.870
Now, what's happening is that
when I set x = 1 here, this

00:25:41.870 --> 00:25:43.050
term is dying.

00:25:43.050 --> 00:25:45.840
This term is going away, because
there's more powers in

00:25:45.840 --> 00:25:47.840
the numerator than in
the denominator.

00:25:47.840 --> 00:25:50.070
This is still 0.

00:25:50.070 --> 00:25:52.330
And this one is gone also.

00:25:52.330 --> 00:25:58.280
So all that's left is B. Now, I
cannot pull that off with a

00:25:58.280 --> 00:25:59.820
single power of x - 1.

00:25:59.820 --> 00:26:02.250
I can't expose the A term.

00:26:02.250 --> 00:26:04.230
It's the B term that
I can expose.

00:26:04.230 --> 00:26:06.170
Because I can multiply through
by this thing squared.

00:26:06.170 --> 00:26:10.390
If I multiply through by just x
- 1, what'll happen here is

00:26:10.390 --> 00:26:12.520
I won't have canceled
this (x - 1 )^2.

00:26:12.520 --> 00:26:13.160
It's useless.

00:26:13.160 --> 00:26:15.020
I still have a 0 in
the denominator.

00:26:15.020 --> 00:26:17.150
I'll have B / 0 when
I plug in x = 1.

00:26:17.150 --> 00:26:22.060
Which I can't use.

00:26:22.060 --> 00:26:32.950
Again, the cover-up method is
giving us B and C, not A.

00:26:32.950 --> 00:26:38.520
Now, for the last term, for A,
I'm going to just have to be

00:26:38.520 --> 00:26:40.380
straightforward about it.

00:26:40.380 --> 00:26:48.780
And so I'll just suggest
for A, plug in

00:26:48.780 --> 00:26:51.260
your favorite number.

00:26:51.260 --> 00:26:59.510
So plug in my favorite number.

00:26:59.510 --> 00:27:01.430
Which is x = 0.

00:27:01.430 --> 00:27:04.860
And you won't be able to
plug in x = 0 if you've

00:27:04.860 --> 00:27:05.700
already used it.

00:27:05.700 --> 00:27:08.440
Here the two numbers we've
already used are x

00:27:08.440 --> 00:27:13.820
= 1 and x = - 2.

00:27:13.820 --> 00:27:18.300
But we haven't used x =
0 yet, so that's good.

00:27:18.300 --> 00:27:21.400
I'm going to plug in now x
= 0 into the equation.

00:27:21.400 --> 00:27:22.450
What do I get?

00:27:22.450 --> 00:27:35.070
I get 0 ^2 + 2 / (- 1) ^2 *
2 is equal to, let's see.

00:27:35.070 --> 00:27:36.800
A is the thing that
I don't know.

00:27:36.800 --> 00:27:44.630
So it's A / - 1 +, B /
x - 1 ^2 so B = 1, so

00:27:44.630 --> 00:27:48.190
that's 1 / (- 1) ^2.

00:27:48.190 --> 00:27:51.760
And then C was 2/3.

00:27:51.760 --> 00:27:55.256
2/3 / x + 2.

00:27:55.256 --> 00:28:00.900
So that's 0 + 2.

00:28:00.900 --> 00:28:02.690
Don't give up at this point.

00:28:02.690 --> 00:28:03.900
This is a lot of algebra.

00:28:03.900 --> 00:28:06.290
You really have to plug
in all these numbers.

00:28:06.290 --> 00:28:08.400
You make one arithmetic mistake
and you're always

00:28:08.400 --> 00:28:09.480
going to get the wrong answer.

00:28:09.480 --> 00:28:16.790
This is very arithmetically
intensive.

00:28:16.790 --> 00:28:18.980
However, it does simplify
at this point.

00:28:18.980 --> 00:28:22.680
We have 2 / 2, that's 1.

00:28:22.680 --> 00:28:27.790
Is equal to - A + 1 + 1/3.

00:28:27.790 --> 00:28:29.050
So let's see.

00:28:29.050 --> 00:28:34.920
A on the other side, this
becomes A = 1/3.

00:28:34.920 --> 00:28:35.520
And that's it.

00:28:35.520 --> 00:28:36.600
This is the end.

00:28:36.600 --> 00:28:40.020
We've we've simplified
our function.

00:28:40.020 --> 00:28:48.290
And now it's easy to integrate.

00:28:48.290 --> 00:28:48.780
Question.

00:28:48.780 --> 00:28:49.350
Another question.

00:28:49.350 --> 00:29:02.010
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:29:02.010 --> 00:29:04.230
PROFESSOR: So the question is,
