00:29:41.610 --> 00:29:42.900
Very good question.

00:29:42.900 --> 00:29:44.490
That's absolutely right.

00:29:44.490 --> 00:29:48.440
This was a 3 by 3 system in
disguise, for these three

00:29:48.440 --> 00:29:51.580
unknowns, A, B and C. What we
started with in the previous

00:29:51.580 --> 00:29:53.950
problem was two variables.

00:29:53.950 --> 00:29:57.430
It's over here, the variables A
and B. And as the degree of

00:29:57.430 --> 00:30:02.900
the denominator goes up, the
number of variables goes up.

00:30:02.900 --> 00:30:05.040
It gets more and more and
more complicated.

00:30:05.040 --> 00:30:06.820
More and more arithmetically
intensive.

00:30:06.820 --> 00:30:09.220
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]

00:30:09.220 --> 00:30:09.910
PROFESSOR: Well, so.

00:30:09.910 --> 00:30:11.170
The question is, how would
you solve it if

00:30:11.170 --> 00:30:12.880
you have two unknowns.

00:30:12.880 --> 00:30:16.610
That's exactly the point here.

00:30:16.610 --> 00:30:18.420
This is a system
of simultaneous

00:30:18.420 --> 00:30:19.560
equations for unknowns.

00:30:19.560 --> 00:30:23.180
And we have little tricks for
isolating single variables.

00:30:23.180 --> 00:30:25.880
Otherwise we're stuck with
solving the whole system.

00:30:25.880 --> 00:30:28.560
And you'd have to solve the
whole system by elimination,

00:30:28.560 --> 00:30:35.980
various other tricks.

00:30:35.980 --> 00:30:38.950
I'll say a little more
about that later.

00:30:38.950 --> 00:30:47.610
Now, I have to get one
step more complicated

00:30:47.610 --> 00:30:53.560
with my next example.

00:30:53.560 --> 00:31:02.860
My next example is going to
have a quadratic factor.

00:31:02.860 --> 00:31:05.900
So still I'm sticking to the
degree of the polynomial and

00:31:05.900 --> 00:31:08.570
the numerator is less than the
degree of the polynomial in

00:31:08.570 --> 00:31:09.660
the denominator.

00:31:09.660 --> 00:31:12.100
And I'm going to take
the case where Q

00:31:12.100 --> 00:31:21.700
has a quadratic factor.

00:31:21.700 --> 00:31:26.140
Let me just again illustrate
this by example.

00:31:26.140 --> 00:31:30.470
I have here (x - 1) (x^2 + 1).

00:31:30.470 --> 00:31:34.630
I'll make it about as
easy as they come.

00:31:34.630 --> 00:31:38.830
Now, the setup will be slightly
different here.

00:31:38.830 --> 00:31:40.510
Here's the setup.

00:31:40.510 --> 00:31:42.570
It's already factored.

00:31:42.570 --> 00:31:44.360
I've already done as
much as I can do.

00:31:44.360 --> 00:31:48.720
I can't factor this x^2 + 1 into
linear factors unless you

00:31:48.720 --> 00:31:49.940
know about complex numbers.

00:31:49.940 --> 00:31:52.380
If you know about complex
numbers this method becomes

00:31:52.380 --> 00:31:53.170
much easier.

00:31:53.170 --> 00:31:55.400
And it comes back to the
cover-up method.

00:31:55.400 --> 00:31:58.370
Which is the way that the
cover-up method was originally

00:31:58.370 --> 00:32:01.060
conceived by heavy side.

00:32:01.060 --> 00:32:04.280
But you won't get to
